		<a name="51055441" width="85%">Topic:</a> 
		The Spam Charge + Thought on Currency		
	</tr>
	
	<tr align="left" valign="top" class="BoardRowA"><td class="BoardRowA" rowspan=3 width="17%"><a href=" http://users.ign.com/about/MiyamotoYoshi?boards=vn " style="color: Black;font-weight: bold;font-style: normal;background-color: Aqua;text-decoration: none;border-top: 1px solid Red;border-bottom: 1px solid Red;border-right: 1px solid Red;border-left: 1px solid Red;">MiyamotoYoshi</a>&nbsp;<a href="/help/default.asp?goto=faqs%2Easp%23stars"><img align=absmiddle src=http://media.ign.com/boardimages/star5.gif border=0 hspace=0 vspace=0 alt="5,260 posts"></a><br><span style="font-size: 8pt;"><!-- WISH & COLL STUFF --><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr class="BoardRowA"><td nowrap="false" class="BoardRowA"><a class="BoardRowBLink" href="http://users.ign.com/collection/MiyamotoYoshi"><font size="1">collection (28)</font></a> | <a class="BoardRowBLink" href="http://users.ign.com/wishlist/MiyamotoYoshi"><font size="1">wishlist (3)</font></a></td></tr></table><!-- /WISH & COLL STUFF	--><span style="font-weight: bold;">Title:</span> EVE Vault Contributor<br><span style="font-weight: bold;">Posts:</span> 5,260<br><span style="font-weight: bold;">Registered:</span> Feb 02<br></span><img border=0 hspace=8 vspace=8 src="http://vaultmedia.ign.com/vnboards/admin/MiyamotoYoshi.gif " width="80" height="80" alt="9910" name="9910" id="9910" class="IconImage"><br></td><td class="BoardRowA" colspan=2 width="83%"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Date Posted:</span>&nbsp;5/30/03 11:16am&nbsp;<span style="font-weight: bold;">Subject:</span> The Spam Charge + Thought on Currency</td></tr><tr valign=top><td class="BoardRowB" colspan=2 width="83%">I keep comparing this to RL.  As a hobby I run <a class=BoardRowBLink href="http://www.EastCoastGames.com">www.EastCoastGames.com</a> .  Because my e-mail address was in several locations on the site mailing list web crawlers found and indexed them.  Since I use various e-mail addresses that all point to the same place, I often get multiple copies of spam and viruses.  Most of the spam seems to deal with adult sites, prescription drugs (especially Viagra), virus software, fake diplomas, and businesss/MLM-like scams.  It's gotten so bad that I have a several e-mail filters.  My most important filter takes basically any mail from people in my addressbook and places it in a &quot;Good&quot; folder.  Then I have several rules to filter out various spam and viruses, an example being any mail that has the word &quot;Viagra&quot; gets moved to the delete folder.  The good rule is always processed first, so if for some reason say my father sent me a classicly tasteless joke involving viagra it would not get deleted.  But if say somebody who is in my corp e-mails me and happens to use one of those words (patent and business for example) then there is a good chance I'll never see it.  Also all the mail that doesn't get moved by a filter I skim to see who they are from and the subject.  Sometimes their is mail here I keep, like mail from IGN.  But all the rest I select as a group and delete.   <br>  <br> So would a spam charge work IRL?  What would the cost be?  Standard mail often includes spam, but the amount of spam is far less then e-mail spam.  E-mail spam costs basically nothing to create.  Real mail costs postage, paper, and printing.  Lets say the cheapest real mail spam costs 40 cents.  40 cents is too much for most of the people who spam e-mail can afford.  40 cents per e-mail for a virus directed at 100,000 people would cost $40,000.  So that may be why anthrax mail was never a big threat!  But what adult website could actually afford $40,000.  Certainly the websites that come from existing media, like playboy.  So the spam would be reduced to an amount similar to real mail spam. <br>  <br> I expect that if CCP designers were asked they would say the spam charge is meant to be comparable to real life.  They might go as far as saying it is a way of marketting a solution to a RL problem (like we often see in other media). <br>  <br> Unfortunatly in real life it would be very difficult to use such a strategy.  There would first have to be a SECURE centralized database of addressbooks.  Also some people would be prone to allowing anybody to e-mail them, like business e-mail addresses.  But in the long run if we could create a technology secure enough to do it and a good cuase to put the money towards . . . it would greatly reduce the amount of spam. <br>  <br> So one of the things I wonder is how much would 100 ISK compare to US dollars?  CCP is in Iceland, what currency does Iceland use?  CCP may have meant ISK to be equivelent to Euros which are very close to US dollars.  Which would mean 100 ISK is over 200 times more then postal costs!  But maybe 1 ISK = 100 Euros.  In which case the cost is reasonable.  The thing that makes ISK hard to compare to real currency is the common goods.  If we new how much a simple meal cost in the EVE universe we could easily compare it to real currencys.  Unfortunately, except for Quafe, most goods are technology based.  Technology based items can vary greatly in cost based on time.  For example 1 gig of hard-drive space today costs what maybe $2?  1 gig in 1980 probably cost $200,000.  Also, are frigates ships most humans own like how most RL humans own cars?  If they are we could compare them to car costs.  But we have no way to know if ship ownership is only for the rich.  Also, even Quafe costs don't help.  The description of one unit of Quafe doesn't give an actual measurement.  For all we know one unit of Quafe is an industrial - keg-size unit.   <br> <p></p><span class="SignatureTitle">-----signature-----</span><div class="SignatureText">Read my Works at <a class=BoardRowBLink href="http://www.EastCoastGames.com">http://www.EastCoastGames.com</a> <br> &quot;Now that I know what I'm without you can't just leave me-&quot; Amy Lee 2003 <br> I must use my powers for evil not good! <br> <a class=BoardRowBLink